02. Studying the laws that determine success of the games.¶

The online store "Streamchik" sells computer games all over the world. Historical data on game sales, user and expert ratings, genres and platforms (for example, Xbox or PlayStation) are available from open sources. We need to identify the patterns that determine the success of the game. This will allow you to bet on a potentially popular product and plan advertising campaigns.

Upon the data before 2016, we are planning a campaign for 2017. The dataframe will be preprocessed below, data gaps will be removed and filled in, graphs will be constructed, the interdependencies of indicators will be investigated, correlation calculated, statistical hypotheses tested, etc. Let's get started.

Preprocessing and preliminary analysis.¶

Description of the data (columns).¶

  • Name — the name of the game
  • Platform — platform
  • Year_of_Release — year of release
  • Genre — the genre of the game
  • NA_sales — sales in North America (millions of copies sold)
  • EU_sales — sales in Europe (millions of copies sold)
  • JP_sales — sales in Japan (millions of copies sold)
  • Other_sales — sales in other countries (millions of copies sold)
  • Critic_Score — critics' score (maximum 100)
  • User_Score — user rating (maximum 10)
  • Rating — rating from the ESRB organization (Eng. Entertainment Software Rating Board). This association determines the rating of computer games and assigns them a suitable age category.

Addition. The codes are assigned by the American ESRB organization. Assignment is on a voluntary basis, a significant part of the games do not have codes. The designations "from children's to adult content": EC, E, E10+, T, M, AO and the so-called "pending pseudo-rating" RP.

A few comments.

  • Sales are not given in monetary terms, but in pieces. In addition, for each game, sales are calculated cumulatively (cumulative total) from the release date of the game to the present (2016).
  • This prevents us from dividing sales by games within the allocated period (regardless of when they were released) and it turns out that we are rather dealing not with sales for the year, as is usually customary, but with the result of sales for the entire period of the game's existence.
  • Such a frame of reference has the following drawback: a game that has not been sold at all for the last 5 years can remain at the top of sales, generally speaking, indefinitely, and it is impossible to single out promising, fast-growing newcomers with such a system of accounting.
  • The system is conservative, for marketing it lacks a typical layout of sales volumes. In the analysis below, the words "growing", "falling" can be used - however, the meaning of these words is more accurately expressed as "more" and "less". For example: "as of 2016, the number of games sold released in 2005 (11 years of sales) is less than the number of games released in 2008 (8 years of sales)."

# let's define the file search function in Linux and Windows folders (if the notebook works locally)

def file_path(name):
    """
File search function (lowercase file name is the function argument) in Linux and Windows folders 
 (if the notebook works locally).

We read the data file with an attempt to take data locally: 4 attempts for the Yandex-server and 
Windows. The file should be located next to the notebook or in the nested directory "datasets". 
    """
    for p in ('/datasets', '', os.path.abspath(""), os.path.abspath("")+'\\datasets\\'):
        pth1 = os.path.join(p, name)
        if os.path.exists(pth1):
            break # if the search is successful, we break the cycle ahead of schedule
    else:
        pth1 = ''
        print(f"The {name} file wasn't found. Make sure that it", 
              'is present in the directory next to the notebook or in a subfolder "/datasets"')
    print('Data reading from:', pth1, '\n')
    return pth1

Processing of missing data on games.¶

232 games do not have a release year. It is very time-consuming to manually restore the years of vyska for 230 games according to Wikipedia. Writing a program to automatically search for data on the web and fill in the gaps is beyond the scope of our project.

The most logical reason for the lack of release dates is that the games are quite old, and statistics on the year of release were added later. However, an Internet search for randomly selected 10 games gives the release years 2001, 2002, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2011, 2017 - therefore, it is more logical to assume some technical reason for the lack of data or intentional mashing of data for the educational task of this project.

  • Our analysis is of a financial nature. Since, financially, sales of games without a release year are 1.1%, and there are also few of them by name (about 2%):
  • 1) we can immediately delete these lines from the dataframe, but data loss is undesirable.
  • 2) fill in the gaps with some arbitrary release year - "2007" or "1985".
  • 3) randomly-evenly fill in the gaps across the range of dates in the dataset from the release date of the platform to 2016 for each game with a missed date (to verify with the release date of the platforms, you will need data from Wikipedia). Let's do it.

def func(platf, year): # function for filling with random numbers in the interval dictionary...2016
    if np.isnan(year):
        return random.randint(rel_year[platf] if platf in rel_year else 1980, 2016)
    else:
        return year   # if not NaN, then leave the available release date

data['year_of_release'] = data.apply(lambda x: func(x.platform, x.year_of_release), axis=1) # filling gaps

Processing of missing data on assessments and ratings.¶

Roughly 10000 of games out of 16000 got ratings and 6000 nan (passes). This lack of rating looks normal, since not all games are produced and /or sold in the United States, Mexico and Canada. In addition, the rating is formally voluntary.

Codes are assigned by the American ESRB organization. The designations "from children's to adult content": EC, E, E10+, T, M, AO and the so-called "pending pseudo-rating" RP.

Market assessment for 2017.¶

  • As it was shown above, the market has been falling since 2009, and no growing platforms - regardless of their position in the sales rating - have been found in the dataframe.
  • The industry is changing very quickly. Let's introduce the concept of "current period" - that is, we will not take into account games released before 2014 and from the remaining ones we will select those who fall slower than the rest.
  • As mentioned in paragraph 1.1, there is no breakdown of sales by year in the dataframe, some downward slope of the charts is normal, since later released games have time to be sold in smaller sizes. The angle of the "normal" slope is unknown, so the analysis will have the right to make an error.

We will select only programs released in 2014 and later (i.e. for 3 years).

# suppressing the output from this cell so that service information is not printed with graphs


def cofunc(pl, ax_n, e_sc, r_sc):     # next we will call this function
    remarks = df10[df10['platform'] == pl][[e_sc, 'total_sales']]  
    plt.figure(figsize = (2.5,2.5))
    sns.scatterplot(data=remarks, x=e_sc, y='total_sales', s=100, legend=False, ax=ax_n)
    ax_n.set_xlabel(r_sc)
    ax_n.set_ylabel('Sales million pieces')
    k = remarks[[e_sc,'total_sales']].corr().round(3)['total_sales'][0]
    ax_n.set_title(f'Platform {pl}, correlation {k}');

The most popular platforms (top 5).¶

In [61]:
# creating a function for grouping data and selecting from columns for charts
def rund(reg_sales): 
    f3 = df10.pivot_table(index=['platform'], values=['na_sales', 'eu_sales', 'jp_sales', 'other_sales'], \
                      aggfunc=['sum'])['sum'].sort_values(by=reg_sales, ascending=False)
    r_sales = list(f3[reg_sales])
    s = sum(r_sales[5:])
    r_sales = list(r_sales[:5])
    r_sales.append(s)
    plats = list(f3.index[:5])
    plats.append('others')
    return r_sales, plats

Step 5. Hypothesis testing.¶

A brief explanation of the process.

  1. The process consists in comparing the probability of the null hypothesis H0 (usually it is the equality of the mean values of two samples) and the alternative hypothesis H1, which in terms of probability theory is the complement of H0 (in sum their probabilities are equal to 1).
  2. The ttest function calculates the P-value. P-value is the probability of obtaining a criterion statistic value equal to the observed one or more atypical compared to the observed one, provided that the null hypothesis is correct.
  3. In our experiments, the P-value is calculated for two samples and further, if this probability (the probability of equality, coincidence) is less than the alpha threshold value, we reject the null hypothesis and accept an alternative one.

Hypothesis: the average user ratings of the Xbox One and PC platforms are the same.¶

In [65]:
df10['platform'].unique() # platform name codes in our database
Out[65]:
array(['PS4', '3DS', 'XOne', 'WiiU', 'PS3', 'X360', 'PC', 'Wii', 'PSV',
       'PS', 'GB', 'PSP', 'DS', 'XB', 'GC', 'GBA', '2600', 'PS2'],
      dtype=object)
In [66]:
# we believe that Xbox One is XOne, we will allocate 2 collections for analysis. NaN is excluded
# since part of numbers does not have a dot and is perceived as integers, we translate it into float

x1 = df10[df10['user_score'].notna()].query('platform == "XOne"')['user_score']
x2 = df10[df10['user_score'].notna()].query('platform == "PC"')['user_score']

H_0: The average user rating of the Xbox One platform is equal to the rating of the PC platform

H_1: The average user rating of the Xbox One platform is NOT equal to the rating of the PC

alpha = 0.01

In [67]:
# results = calling a method to test the hypothesis
results = st.ttest_ind(x1, x2, equal_var=False)
# alpha = setting the significance level value
alpha = 0.01
# output of the p-value value to the screen
print(results.pvalue)
# conditional operator with the output of a response string
if results.pvalue < alpha:
    print('We reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print('Failed to reject the null hypothesis.')

0.13286822531130538
Failed to reject the null hypothesis.
In [68]:
# let's show the average estimates of Xbox One and PC users

round(x1.mean(), 2), round(x2.mean(), 2)
Out[68]:
(6.59, 6.31)

Statistical analysis of samples (their mean and variance) shows that the average user rating of the Xbox One platform is equal to the rating of the PC platform. The measured mismatch of their averages is statistically likely (not lower than the alpha threshold).

Hypothesis: average user ratings of Action and Sports genres are different.¶

In [69]:
# let's select 2 collections with data for statistical analysis from the dataframe

x1 = df10[df10['user_score'].notna()].query('genre == "Action"')['user_score']
x2 = df10[df10['user_score'].notna()].query('genre == "Sports"')['user_score']

H_0: The average user rating of the Action genre is equal to the rating of the Sports genre

H_1: The average user rating of the Action genre is NOT equal to the rating of the Sports

alpha = 0.01

In [70]:

# alpha = setting the significance level value
alpha = 0.01
# getting of the p-value value on the screen

We reject the null hypothesis.

Based on the available data, at the significance level of 1%, there are grounds to reject the null hypothesis about the equality of the average values of user ratings (reviews) of the Action and Sports genres in favor of an alternative hypothesis.

In [71]:
# print the average estimates of users of the Action and Sports genres

round(x1.mean(), 2), round(x2.mean(), 2)
Out[71]:
(6.77, 5.36)

Statistical analysis of samples (their mean and variance) shows that the average user rating of the Action genre is NOT equal to the rating of the Sports genre. The measured discrepancy of their averages is statistically likely (not lower than the alpha 0.01 threshold). That is, the hypothesis announced in the title is correct (H0 was its opposite, complement).

Conclusions.¶

As can be seen from the graphs above, not only the number of games, but also sales as such, have been increasing significantly since the year of release in 1995 and reach a maximum for releases in 2009. By now (2016), the market is falling financially. The period 1980-1995 can be considered a stage of smooth development, and the year 1995 is the start of the computer games boom, which is a thing of the past.

It is most likely that next year the leadership will remain with the PS4 and XOne platforms, but 3DS will be able to compete with them in the coming years, since its schedule has a more flat appearance. WiiU grew in the period 2011-2012 and equaled the sales of the PS3. So this is also a strong player who can fight from next year for a place in the top three.

On the chart of the scope of the PS4, their sales are large due to emissions (see the chart "Platform leaders for 2016 (2014+ releases)"). That is, they have "star games" that contribute to gross sales, but the second half of the list are stable middle-class, already without emissions.

On the Wii and WiiU platforms, the median value is quite high for non-users, that is, sales are provided by fewer at a higher price, similarly for the PS2 and DS platforms.

Correlation for 9 platforms of sales leaders in the context of sales - critics' ratings. There is not enough data for calculation for GBA, N64, PS. There are only 3 ratings for DS and PS2 platforms, in the first case the correlation is very high negative, in the second high positive. For 3DS, PC, PS4, PS3 platforms, the correlation of sales with critics' ratings is weak, very weak, weak and average.

Correlation for 9 platforms of sales leaders in the context of sales - user ratings. There is too little data for GBA, DS, N64, PS, PS2. For PC, PS3, PS4, the correlation is very weak, and negative. Only for 3DS the correlation is positive, but also very weak.

On the boxplot chart, Shooter is a clear leader in the period 2014-2016, its median is ahead of the 3rd quartile in almost all other genres. Next, with a noticeable lag, is the Sports genre. Inside the median, the WiiU platform is a leader in Racing, Fighting, Sports. According to Shooter leader XOne, in the genre of Misc leader Wii. In terms of sales, the Action genre is in the lead, Shooter is in second place. PS4 leads in the genres of Action, Shooter, Sports, and in the genre of Role-Playing passes 3DS in first place.

In North America, the PS4 is in the lead, with XOne in second place. In Europe, the unequivocal leader is PS4, followed by XOne with a lag. In Japan, 3DS is the absolute leader, followed by PS4 and PSV. In other regions, the total leader is PS4 (as in Europe) and behind it with a margin of XOne, and PS3 is in 3rd place. Interestingly, in Japan, almost the entire market is disassembled under 5 leaders, others occupy a very small share.

Shooter and Action genres are leading in North America. Action and Shooter genres are leading in Europe. In Japan, the leaders are Role-Playing and Action. In the rest of the world, the Action and Shooter genres are leading. The Sports genre is popular everywhere (3rd place), but not in Japan, the Japanese have the "other" genres in 3rd place.

According to the ESRB ratings, North American and European data are almost the same. The rest of the regions practically repeat this trend, only on a smaller scale (the curve is shifted down relative to Europe and North America). And the Japanese market has its own specifics: its line has a peak in the field of programs with the label no_esrb. The no_esrb label has almost the same level of sales in the European, North American and Japanese markets.

Statistics. "Hypothesis: average user ratings of Xbox One and PC platforms are the same" was accepted with alpha 0.01. Hypothesis: "average user ratings of Action and Sports genres are different" was accepted with alpha 0.01.
